Term Deposit Sale Project

Data Analysis and Modelling by: Varun Kulkarni (kulkarnivarun@outlook.com)

Goal¶

Using the data collected from existing customers, build a model that will help the marketing team identify potential customers who are relatively more likely to subscribe term deposit and thus increase their hit ratio.

Data Source¶

bank-full.csv (https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Bank+Marketing)

Tasks¶

  • Exploratory Data Analysis
    • Univariate Analysis
    • Multivariate Analysis
  • Prepare Data for Analytics
    • Ensure the attribute types are correct
    • Transform the data i.e. scale / normalize if required
    • Create training set and test set in ratio of 70:30
  • Create Ensemble Models
    • Logistic Regression Model
    • Decision Tree Model
    • Ensemble Model using Bagging
    • Ensemble Model using Random Forest
    • Ensemble Model using Adaptive Boosting
    • Ensemble Model using Gradient Boosting
    • Comparing All Models
  • Conclusion

Observations of numerical attributes:¶

  1. age: Age is a continuous attribute. Minimum is 18 years and maximum is 95. The distribution looks pretty normal (with similar mean and median ~40), with some outliers. Majority of values between 30 and 60 years approximately. There does not seem to be invalid values reported.
  1. balance: Indicates the balance (in some currency) in the account. The distribution of this attribute is highly right skewed with vast difference between mean (1362.27) and the median (448.0), with maximum of 102127.00. The minimum value of -8019.0 indicates presence of negative (incorrect) values, which need to be fixed.
  1. duration: Indicates previous contact duration in seconds. Data distribution looks right skewed, with lot of customers contacted for smaller amount of time. There seems to be considerable number of outliers.
  1. campaign: Indicates the number of times the client was contacted during the campaign. Over half of the clients were contacted just 1 or 2 times. The distribution is slightly right skewed with mean at 2.7 and median at 2.0. There are considerable number of outliers, which need to be treated.
  1. pdays: Indicates number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted. -1 tells us the person has not been contacted or contact period is beyond 900 days. There are about 37K such records, indicating most of the clients are not contacted recently. The data is right skewed with large number of outliers that needs to be treated.
  1. previous: Indicates number of contacts performed before this campaign, for this client. Data is highly right skewed with large number of outliers present.

To summarize:

  1. Attribute balance has some negative values that should be fixed. Perhaps just considering their absolute values.
  2. Attributes age, balance, duration, campaign, pdays and previous are skewed and contain outliers. A robust scaler can be used to scale these attributes to handle outliers.
  3. None of the numerical attributes seems to have missing or duplicated data.

Observations of categorical / ordinal attributes:¶

  1. job: This attribute has 12 different job categories. Based on the counts, Blue-collar, Management professionals and Technicians are among the top three job categories. There are some 'unknown' values which need to be treated.
  1. marital : This attribute has three categories - married, single and divorced. More than 27 thousand are married, over 12 thousand are single and over 5 thousand are divorced. No incorrect imputations observed.
  1. education: This attribute has three categories namely primary, secondary and tertiary. There are some unknown values, which need to be replaced based on real world observations and inference.
  1. default: It's a binary categorical attribute with yes or no values indicating whether the customer has credit in default or not. Majority of the customers (over 44,000) customers do not have credit in default. No incorrect imputations observed.
  1. housing: This variable is also binary categorical attribute with yes or no values, indicating whether the customer has housing loan or not. More than half of the records (over 25,000) have housing loan.
  1. loan : This is also a binary categorical attribute with yes or no values. It indicates whether the customer has a personal loan or not. Most of the customers, (over 37,000) have not opted for personal loan.
  1. contact: Communication type is a categorical attribute, with two main categories namely cellular and telephone, indicating two main ways to communicate with the customer. There are some unknown values, which need to be fixed.
  1. month: This categorical attribute indicates which month of the year, the customer was last contacted. Based on the distribution, month of May has the maximum number of contacts, followed by July and August. There seems to be no incorrect imputations of the data.
  1. poutcome: Has three main categories namely success, failure and other. There are significant number of unknowns (over 39,000).
  1. day: Indicates the day of the month, the customer was last contacted. Data distribution looks fairly normal with similar values for mean and median. No outliers or incorrect values observed.
  1. Target: Binary categorical variable, that tell us whether the client has subscribed to a term deposit or not (Yes or No). Significant number of customers (about 40000), have not subscribed to the term deposit. No incorrect imputations observed.

Attributes job, education, contact and poutcome have too many unknowns which needs to be treated. We can perhaps use real world intuition to reduce / eliminate the unknown values.

Multivariate Analysis (8 Marks) ¶

Before we proceed, let's perform necessary data transformations for multivariate analysis:

  1. Consider absolute values for 'balance' to remove the negative values.
  2. Replace unknowns from 'contact' with 'cellular' and 'telephone' proportionately.
  3. Try to reduce unknowns from 'job' by inferring from education and age.
  4. Try to reduce unknowns from 'education', by inferring from age and job.
In [10]:
# Create a copy for data transformations.
data_df = bank_df.copy(deep=True)

# Get absolute values for balance
data_df['balance'] = data_df.balance.abs()

# Replace unknown values of 'contact' variable proportionately with cellular and telephone
vc = data_df.contact.value_counts()
cell_percent =  vc['cellular'] / (vc['cellular'] + vc['telephone'])
cell_count = int(round(vc['unknown'] * cell_percent))

contact_values = data_df.contact.values.tolist()
for idx in range(len(contact_values)):
    if contact_values[idx] == 'unknown':
        if cell_count > 0:
            contact_values[idx] = 'cellular'
            cell_count -= 1
        else:
            contact_values[idx] = 'telephone'
data_df['contact'] = contact_values

print("Number of customers left with negative balance: ", data_df[data_df.balance < 0].shape[0])
print("Number of customers left with unknown contact type: ", data_df[data_df.contact == 'unknown'].shape[0])

Number of customers left with negative balance:  0
Number of customers left with unknown contact type:  0

# Based on above observations - 

# Let's replace unknown job values of customers above 60 years with 'retired'
data_df.loc[(data_df.job == 'unknown') & (data_df.age > 60), 'job'] = 'retired'

# Let's mark all customers, with unknown job values, between age 15 and 25 as students
data_df.loc[(data_df.job == 'unknown') & ((data_df.age > 15) & (data_df.age <= 25)), 'job'] = 'student'

# Based on distribution of age alone it's difficult to further infer job values.
# Let's mark the remaining customers (about 115) as unemployed for simplicity.
data_df.loc[data_df.job == 'unknown', 'job'] = 'unemployed'

As seen above, it's difficult to infer the education levels based on distribution of age. Let's find the most frequent education level in each job category. Then, replace the unknown value with education level that is most frequent in that customer's job category.

In [16]:
# Get popular education levels per job category
freq_edu_per_job = data_df.groupby('job').apply(lambda x: x['education'].value_counts().index[0])
job_edu_dict = {x:y for (x,y) in zip(freq_edu_per_job.index, freq_edu_per_job.values)}
print("Popular education level per job:")
for job, edu in job_edu_dict.items():
    print("{0} \t: {1}".format(job, edu))

  • The average value for pdays (number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign), is more for customers who have opted for term deposit. Indicating, customers who were not bothered immediately after previous campaign, responded well for term deposit.

def get_model_perf(model, xtr, xte, ytr, yte):
    ''' Method to get performance metrics of the model
        model - fitted classifier instance.
        xtr - train data
        ytr - train labels
        xte - test data
        yte - test labels'''
    
    ypred = model.predict(xte)
    
    perf_dict = {}
    # Get confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(yte, ypred, labels=[1, 0])
    tp, tn, fp, fn = cm[0][0], cm[1][1], cm[1][0], cm[0][1] 
    perf_dict['True Positives'] = tp
    perf_dict['True Negatives'] = tn
    perf_dict['False Positives'] = fp
    perf_dict['False Negatives'] = fn
        
    # Get train and test accuracies   
    train_score = model.score(xtr, ytr)
    test_score  = model.score(xte, yte)
    perf_dict['Train Accuracy'] = round(train_score*100.0, 3)
    perf_dict['Test Accuracy']  = round(test_score*100.0, 3)

    # Get area under the curve
    roc_auc = roc_auc_score(yte, ypred)
    perf_dict['ROC AUC'] = round(roc_auc, 3)

    # Get precision, recall and f1-score
    ps = precision_score(yte, ypred)
    rs = recall_score(yte, ypred)
    f1s = f1_score(yte, ypred, average='macro')
    perf_dict['Percision Score'] = round(ps, 3)
    perf_dict['Recall Score']    = round(rs, 3)
    perf_dict['F1-score']        = round(f1s, 3)

    return perf_dict


def draw_tree(dtree_clf, dot_file, image_file, class_names, feature_names):
    ''' Method to draw decision tree.
        dtree_clf - Fitted Decision Tree Classifier instance
        dot_file - dot file name with .dot extension
        image_file - image file name with .png extension
        class_names - labels
        feature_names - list of independent features'''
    
    tree_file = open(dot_file,'w')
    dot_data = tree.export_graphviz(dtree_model, 
                                    out_file = tree_file, 
                                    feature_names = feature_names, 
                                    class_names = class_names, 
                                    filled=True, rounded=True, special_characters=True)
    tree_file.close()

    # Works only if "dot" command works on your machine
    command = "dot -Tpng {0} -o {1}".format(dot_file, image_file)
    retCode = system(command)
    if retCode > 0:
        print("Error while diplaying tree! error code: " + str(retCode))
    else:
        display(Image(image_file))

def draw_confusion_matrix(model, xte, yte, classes=['Yes', 'No'], labels=[1, 0], title='Confusion Matrix'):
    '''Method to draw the confusion matrix
        model - classifier instance that is already fitted
        xte - test data
        yte - test labels
        classes - classification categories
        labels - label indexes'''
    
    # Inference
    ypred = model.predict(xte)
    
    # Get confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(yte, ypred, labels=labels)
    cm_df = pd.DataFrame(cm, index=classes, columns=classes)

    # Plot the matrix
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,7))
    sns.heatmap(cm_df, annot=True, linewidths=0.3, annot_kws={"fontsize":15}, fmt='g')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel("Predicted")
    plt.ylabel("Truth")
    plt.show()

Observations and reasoning for the best algorithm:¶

Based on above table of metrics, Random Forest demonstrates the best classification performance. RandomForest is an ensemble of decision trees, generally trained via bagging method, typically with max_samples set to the size of the training set. Ideally, the BaggingClassifier with decision tree should perform equally well as RandomForestClassifier.

However, the RandomForestClassifer is more optimized for Decision Trees. It introduces extra randomness by selecting subset of variables randomly when growing trees, instead of searching for the very best feature when splitting a node. Thus, the algorithm results in greater tree diversity. This results in higher bias for a lower variance, generally yielding an overall better model. The Random Forest has best train and test accuracies along with best ROC AUC. It also has the best F1-score, indicating best weighted average of precision and recall scores. Mainly, the model has the least False Negatives (Type II errors).

Logistic Regression has the lowest classification performance, as it has the lowest ROC AUC. Although Decision Tree has lower recall score, it has the best precision score and least False Positives (Type I errors). Almost all the models performed equally well as the features were already scaled. Feature scaling helped improve performance of all models and is an essential step in the data analysis.

Conclusion ¶

The goal is to help the marketing team identify potential customers who are relatively more likely to subscribe to term deposit and thus increase their hit ratio.

For the given business use case, the cost of Type II errors (False Negatives) is significant. Type II errors will result in decreased hit ratio implying losing potential customers for term deposit. For this reason, Random Forest model would be a good candidate model, as it has the lowest False Negatives with highest recall score.

If the marketing team intends to focus more on the cost of marketing per customer, then the Decision Tree model would be a good candidate, as it has lowest Type I errors (False positives).

Thoughts on further model improvements: The amount of unknowns in the dataset for various attributes must be minimized by collecting more data wherever necessary. Especially, the outcome of the previous campaign (poutcome). Additional data such as geographical location, salaries, gender, credit scores, etc. related to customers, can be added for better understanding the outcome.
